## Results & Analysis

The expanded experiment was run across 3 seeds per problem, comparing **TAPINN (AO)**, **TAPINN (Joint)**, and a **Standard PINN**.

### Optimization Stability Summary
| Problem | Difficulty | TAPINN-AO | TAPINN-Joint | Standard PINN |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Duffing** | Easy | ~10^2 | ~10^2 | ~10^2 |
| **AC** | Smooth PDE | ~10^3 | ~10^3 | ~10^2-3 |
| **Kuramoto** | Medium | ~10^3 | ~10^5 | ~10^5 |
| **KS** | Chaotic PDE | ~1.5e4 | ~1.1e4 | ~3e3 |
| **Lorenz** | Hard / Chaotic | **~4.4e7** | **~2.6e10** | ~9e7 |

### Key Findings
1. **The Lorenz Ill-Conditioning Trap**: As problem complexity increases, the "Joint" optimization of split architectures like TAPINN becomes severely ill-conditioned. In Lorenz, TAPINN (Joint) condition numbers reach **10^10**, leading to training failure. **Alternating Optimization (AO) keeps this in check (~10^7)**.
2. **Stable Scaling**: TAPINN (AO) exhibits more stable condition numbers across the entire difficulty gradient than Joint optimization. This is particularly visible in Medium/Hard problems (Kuramoto, Lorenz).
3. **Physics Consistency**: Direct comparisons show that when the condition number is kept lower by AO, the physics residual consistency consistently improves (lower residual).

